               <msContents>
                  
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_Bodl_916-item1">
                     <author key="person_44413993">Reginald Pecock</author>
                     <title key="work_4233">The Donet</title>
                     <incipit>In nomme patris et filii et spiritus sancti. Here bigynnyþ þe prolog.</incipit>
                     <note>The title is suggested in the prologue ('þe donet or key of goddis lawe, or [...] cristen religioun'), and the treatise, being in the form of a dialogue in two parts (see fol. 47), is intended 
                        to serve as an introduction to, and summary of, the author's <title>Rule of Christian Religion</title></note>
                     <incipit type="prol.">For as moche as the book ycallid the reule</incipit>
                     <incipit type="text"> Fadir. What is a man. Sone. A man is a quick body</incipit>
                     <note>At fol. 14 is a list of some works by Pecock, but there is no direct indication of the author</note>
                     <note>This appears to be the only extant manuscript of the treatise, but Elsie Vaughan Hitchcock notes that this is is certainly not the original manuscript, and was 
                        written out fair by the scribe, and then corrected by another hand (<title>The Donet</title>, EETS 156 [Oxford, 1921], <ref target="https://archive.org/details/donetpeco00peco/page/n16/mode/1up">p. xi</ref>)</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="enm">Middle English</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                  
               </msContents>
